    {
        "user": "U0ATM0LSFB8",
        "type": "message",
        "ts": "1777947651.871669",
        "edited": {
            "user": "U0ATM0LSFB8",
            "ts": "1777947715.000000"
        },
        "client_msg_id": "0f8c3402-c052-40d5-86ee-d6377db833d8",
        "text": "As someone who only ever bothers with Nvim distros, defaults to fish shell and generally rarely checks the man doc let alone the config's mandoc, as someone who doesn't really do programming recreationally,  I had a rather few eye opening moments this year where the 5 minutes I spent looking at config manuals made incredible impact on the comfort of my computing environment. These range from undervolting a laptop to learning a simple tmux cmd.\n\nThe reason I'm sharing is that these moments made me realize that as precious those 5 minutes are, they can actually be very well spent at customization. Reading manuals, I tend to associate that with nights wasted distro hopping and desktop ricing of my youth but those are but extremes and swinging back to the opposite extreme only had me settling for a sharp and hard defaults. We're all so different after all.\n\nAnecdote aside, one thing that really helped me was having a better understanding of what made me uncomfortable. I maintained a todo list for personal computing maintaince tasks (which I usually tackle when procrastinating something else). I used atuin to analyze what commands I used most. I used LLMs too in some cases, they're a big help when it comes to sanding edges.\n\nCategorically, I (and everyone here) have always been and will always be a statical outlier when it comes to customizing their computer. That being said, the virtue there is really real me thinks. Defaults are overrated.",
        "team": "T5TCAFTA9",
        "user_team": "T5TCAFTA9",
        "source_team": "T5TCAFTA9",
        "user_profile": {
            "avatar_hash": "g79842c7c389",
            "image_72": "https:\/\/secure.gravatar.com\/avatar\/79842c7c389426d76e2bb53fc48f8b98.jpg?s=72&d=https%3A%2F%2Fa.slack-edge.com%2Fdf10d%2Fimg%2Favatars%2Fava_0012-72.png",
            "first_name": "dman-os",
            "real_name": "dman-os",
            "display_name": "",
            "team": "T5TCAFTA9",
            "name": "pectin-erased-unit",
            "is_restricted": false,
            "is_ultra_restricted": false
        },
        "thread_ts": "1777902184.042729",
        "parent_user_id": "UJBAJNFLK",
        "blocks": [
            {
                "type": "rich_text",
                "block_id": "HLMJ1",
                "elements": [
                    {
                        "type": "rich_text_section",
                        "elements": [
                            {
                                "type": "text",
                                "text": "As someone who only ever bothers with Nvim distros, defaults to fish shell and generally rarely checks the man doc let alone the config's mandoc, as someone who doesn't really do programming recreationally,  I had a rather few eye opening moments this year where the 5 minutes I spent looking at config manuals made incredible impact on the comfort of my computing environment. These range from undervolting a laptop to learning a simple tmux cmd.\n\nThe reason I'm sharing is that these moments made me realize that as precious those 5 minutes are, they can actually be very well spent at customization. Reading manuals, I tend to associate that with nights wasted distro hopping and desktop ricing of my youth but those are but extremes and swinging back to the opposite extreme only had me settling for a sharp and hard defaults. We're all so different after all.\n\nAnecdote aside, one thing that really helped me was having a better understanding of what made me uncomfortable. I maintained a todo list for personal computing maintaince tasks (which I usually tackle when procrastinating something else). I used atuin to analyze what commands I used most. I used LLMs too in some cases, they're a big help when it comes to sanding edges.\n\nCategorically, I (and everyone here) have always been and will always be a statical outlier when it comes to customizing their computer. That being said, the virtue there is really real me thinks. Defaults are overrated."
                            }
                        ]
                    }
                ]
            }
        ],
        "reactions": [
